Since you're `exec`-ing into a broker pod, the CLI tools are on the pod, so the bootstrap server is local. All of these are **read-only** (consuming doesn't remove messages).

The core one — read messages and grep for your search string:

```bash
kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --from-beginning \
  --property print.key=true --property print.timestamp=true \
  --timeout-ms 15000 | grep '<search-string>'
```

`--from-beginning` reads the whole topic; `--timeout-ms` makes the consumer exit after that many ms of no new messages (otherwise it hangs waiting forever). Drop `--from-beginning` to only see new/live messages.

A few variations depending on what you need:

**Search only recent messages** (last N per partition — much faster on a big topic):

```bash
kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --offset -<N> --partition 0 \
  --timeout-ms 10000 | grep '<search-string>'
```

`--offset` needs a specific `--partition`; repeat per partition, or use `--max-messages` instead to cap total across all partitions.

**Case-insensitive, with context, show partition/offset** (helps you locate the message):

```bash
kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --from-beginning --timeout-ms 15000 \
  --property print.partition=true --property print.offset=true \
  --property print.key=true --property print.timestamp=true \
  | grep -i '<search-string>'
```

**Search within a time window** — first resolve the offset for a start time, then consume from it:

```bash
# offset at/after a timestamp (epoch millis) for partition 0
kafka-run-class.sh kafka.tools.GetOffsetShell \
  --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 --topic <topic> --time <epoch-ms>
# then consume from that offset:
kafka-console-consumer.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --topic <topic> --partition 0 --offset <offset-from-above> \
  --timeout-ms 10000 | grep '<search-string>'
```

A few practical notes:

- **If the topic is large, always bound the search** with `--max-messages`, `--offset -<N>`, or a time window — a full `--from-beginning` scan on a high-volume topic can read millions of records and take a long time.
- **Consumer group offsets aren't touched** by console-consumer (it uses a throwaway group), so this won't interfere with your real consumers.
- **If auth/TLS is enabled** on the cluster (common for MSK), add `--consumer.config /path/to/client.properties` with the security settings, or the consumer will fail to connect. Check whether your other consumers use such a file.
- **For counting matches** instead of printing, pipe to `grep -c '<search-string>'`.

